5.2 World Models and Memory (Predictive-State View)
Predictive world model. In a POMDP, what matters for decision-making is the ability to predict future observations under candidate action sequences. Accordingly, we use predictive world model to mean any internal mechanism sufficient to determine (or approximate) the test probabilities . In the language of predictive-state representations (PSRs), the vector
is the predictive state. For sufficiently rich , is decision-sufficient; in finite POMDPs, the belief state is one such representation [kaelbling1998].
Memory (representation of history). We model the agent’s internal memory abstractly as a representation through which the policy factors:
We say that is decision-sufficient for a test family if determines the optimal bet for all tests in that family, and accordingly that is -based, since depends on only through for all betting goals . Our selection theorems show that achieving low average regret on separating betting goals forces the agent’s memory to refine the predictive-state partition induced by ; representations that alias histories with distinct predictive states incur unavoidable regret.
