7 Discussion
This work develops a general method for deriving representation-theoretic conclusions from performance guarantees, known as “selection theorems” [wentworth2021selection]. Across fully observed and partially observed settings, we showed that low average-case regret on structured families of action-conditioned prediction tasks selects for predictive internal structure. In fully observed environments, this yields quantitative recovery of the interventional kernel under stochastic policies and average regret. In partially observed environments, it yields no-aliasing results forcing belief-like, decision-sufficient memory. Further corollaries show that structured task families induce additional internal organization: block-structured tests select for informational modularity, shifting mixtures select for regime-tracking state, and minimal low-regret representations converge (up to invertible recoding) to the same decision-relevant partition.
To our knowledge, these are the first quantitative selection theorems linking average-case regret over structured task families to necessary predictive-state and memory structure under partial observability. While prior work [sondik1971, kaelbling1998] establishes sufficiency of belief representations for optimal control, and related literatures derive structural consequences from rationality axioms or specialized regulation settings, our results show that regret-bounded competence alone—without worst-case optimality or determinism—imposes concrete internal constraints.
A unifying perspective is that robust competence under uncertainty compresses the space of admissible internal representations. When the evaluation distribution places nontrivial mass on large-margin predictive distinctions, any policy that aliases those distinctions incurs constant regret. Thus, performance pressure shapes internal structure: predictive state, memory, modular decomposition, and regime-tracking variables are not merely architectural assumptions but consequences of task demands.
These results resonate with empirical trends in representation learning and NeuroAI. Increasingly general task demands correlate with increasingly aligned representations across architectures and modalities, including alignment between artificial and biological systems in visual [yamins2014performance, khaligh2014deep, cadena2019deep, nayebi2018task, Zhuang2021, nayebi2021unsupervised, nayebi2022], auditory [kell2018task, feather2019metamers], motor [sussillo2015neural, michaels2020goal], memory [banino2018vector, nayebi2021explaining, sorscher2023unified], world-modeling [bear2021physion, nayebi2023neural], and language [schrimpf2021neural] brain areas. In fact, these observations are not restricted to single brain areas either, recent work [keller2025autonomous] has found strong correspondences between autonomous agents and whole-brain data in animals such as larval zebrafish, which are accessible by modern tools. The Contravariance Principle in NeuroAI [cao2024explanatory] and the Platonic Representation Hypothesis in AI [huh2024platonic], both hypothesize that sufficiently general learning pressures drive convergence toward a shared statistical model of reality. Our selection-theoretic results provide a complementary formal lens: when agents must succeed across sufficiently rich uncertainty-sensitive tasks, their internal states must encode the predictive structure that separates those tasks. This offers a principled account of why task-general systems often exhibit convergent, brain-like representational structure: convergence need not be accidental, but can arise from shared competence constraints, and are in fact reversibly mappable to one another, as we show in Corollary 5.
As AI systems become increasingly robust and adaptive, our results suggest that certain organizational regularities should emerge across architectures: global information integration, modular specialization under task factorization, and belief-like predictive state representations under partial observability. These regularities closely mirror themes from cognitive architecture and theories of consciousness (e.g. global broadcast and modular processing [baars1997theater, baars2019consciousness, blum2022theory, blum2024ai]), not as metaphysical commitments, but as structural consequences of decision-theoretic pressures.
In other words, rather than viewing robust agency as distinct from such considerations, our results suggest overall that competent decision-making under uncertainty directly implies many of these core features shared across cognitive theories. More empirical evidence is needed from the brain sciences as to the necessary and sufficient observables to support such theories [cogitate2025adversarial], so we make no such claims here—it could very well be that how these components of world modeling, memory, and modularity are combined that matters for subjective experience (not merely having them, as we have demonstrated here111It is worth noting though that individual differences across brains leading to similar behavior [feather2025brain] make this possibility unlikely, but not ruled out.).
Therefore, these structural results are relevant to emerging discussions about increasingly agentic AI systems [long2024taking]. If strong task-general performance selects for persistent internal state, regime-tracking variables that resemble modulation mechanisms studied in affective neuroscience [ekman1992argument, barrett2017theory], and unified predictive representations, then advancing capability will tend to produce systems with increasingly rich internal organization. Understanding the structural signatures that accompany robust agency may therefore inform ongoing empirical and philosophical analysis of advanced AI systems.
In sum, selection theorems provide a bridge between capability and structure. They show how robust generalization under uncertainty constrains internal organization, offering a formal normative framework for understanding the systematic emergence of world models, memory, modularity, and representational convergence in increasingly capable artificial agents.
